COOPERATIVE AGREEMENT WITH THE UNIVERSITY OF MARYLAND TO ASSIST FSIS IN DEVELOPING TWO SEPARATE RISK ASSESSMENT MODELS IN CHICKEN AND IN TURKEY. THESE PRODUCTION TO CONSUMPTION RISK MODELS WILL ESTIMATE REDUCTIONS IN FOODBORNE ILLNESS ATTRIBUTED TO CHICKEN AND TURKEY RESULTING FROM CONTROL OF SALMONELLA. SPECIFICALLY, THE MODELS WILL PREDICT THE IMPACT OF THREE SCENARIOS.  FIRST, THE IMPACT OF CONTROLLING SALMONELLA PREVALENCE, LEVELS(ENUMERATION), AND SUBTYPES OF PUBLIC HEALTH CONCERN PRE AND POST HARVEST. SECOND, THE IMPACT OF IMPLEMENTING PRE, POST AND COMBINED PRE AND POST HARVEST CONTROLS. THIRD, THE IMPACT OF ESTABLISHING CRITERIA LIMITING SALMONELLA PREVALENCE, LEVELS OR SUBTYPES, OR REQUIRING A SPECIFIED REDUCTION IN A RELEVANT INDICATOR ORGANISM.
